UID:28shf3576ttb4ud4jh2itura8h@google.com
CREATED:20220216T171529Z
DESCRIPTION:<p>The end of a star can take many forms\, most of them control
 led by the mass of a star when fusion at the star’s core can no longer supp
 ort that mass. &nbsp\;In this talk we will explore how stars begin their li
 fe cycle and how the difference in their masses determines how they will en
 d. &nbsp\;</p><p>An Observing Lab is an opportunity to learn a bit about th
 e astrophysics of stars and the interesting objects that result that are de
 finitely within the reach of our telescopes at the Robert Ferguson Observat
 ory. &nbsp\;Come prepared to take your observing notes and dressed warmly s
 o you can take advantage of observing visually through the 8-inch refractor
  and the 40-inch reflector\, as well as through the personal telescopes of 
 our knowledgeable docents. &nbsp\;Some of the best observing will be using 
 the CCD camera on the 20-inch Ritchey Chretien reflector for the really dee
 p deep sky objects. &nbsp\;In addition to our stated date for this event\, 
 there will be a rain date in case poor weather doesn’t permit us to observe
 .</p><p>Purchase tickets at <a href="http://rfo.simpletix.com">rfo.simpleti
 x.com</a>&nbsp\;</p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20220216T171529Z
LOCATION:Robert Ferguson Observatory\, 2605 Adobe Canyon Rd\, Kenwood\, CA 
 95452\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Observing Lab ~ Star Death
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
