UID:5bp966nblc6bg63dhsdd3kjkg1@google.com
CREATED:20241018T202325Z
DESCRIPTION:The end of a star can take many forms\, most of them controlled
  by the mass of a star when fusion at the star’s core can no longer support
  that mass.  In this talk we will explore how stars begin their life cycle 
 and how the difference in their masses determines how they will end.  \nAn 
 Observing Lab is an opportunity to learn a bit about the astrophysics of st
 ars and the interesting objects that result that are definitely within the 
 reach of our telescopes at the Robert Ferguson Observatory.  Come prepared 
 to take your observing notes and dressed warmly so you can take advantage o
 f observing visually through the 8-inch refractor and the 40-inch reflector
 \, as well as through the personal telescopes of our knowledgeable docents.
   Some of the best observing will be using the CCD camera on the 20-inch Ri
 tchey Chretien reflector for the really deep deep sky objects. \nIn case of
  poor weather\, the alternate date is October 2\, 2025.  \nPurchase tickets
  at rfo.simpletix.com
LAST-MODIFIED:20251002T201126Z
LOCATION:Robert Ferguson Observatory\, 2605 Adobe Canyon Rd\, Kenwood\, CA 
 95452\, USA
SEQUENCE:2
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Observing Lab ~ Star Death - CANCELLED DUE TO WEATHER
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
