DESCRIPTION:Move over\, summer Perseids. December's Geminid shower is consi
 dered the best and most reliable meteor shower of the year. Under dark clea
 r skies\, counts can reach 50-100 per hour or more on peak night. But this 
 is only one of many factors that set these meteors apart from all other sho
 wers. Their speed and composition create meteors that flare low in the atmo
 sphere\, are easier to spot\, and leave bright\, often yellow\, trails. <br
 ><br>This is one of the very few showers visible all night long. What cause
 s this dazzling display and why does it occur at this time of year? Come le
 arn about these unique meteors\, their unusual history\, and their mysterio
 us origin. <br><br>This Focus Night equips you for a Geminid ”peak” experie
 nce. Unlike planets that can hang around for months\, a meteor shower is on
 ly visible over a short period of time. Highest counts will occur later in 
 the night and into the early morning hours Dec 12th-14th. You will learn ab
 out different kinds of showers\, how best to view them\, and how to underst
 and what you are seeing. You’ll also discover factors that influence meteor
  counts and how to optimize your viewing tonight and tomorrow. <br><br>Plan
  to be in the classroom by 6:55PM to ensure you have a good seat. Program b
 egins promptly at 7:00PM . Sales are limited to 40 guests so we can provide
  a more personal experience. Allow generous time to arrive and park. <br><b
 r>Please visit <a href="https://rfo.simpletix.com/" target="_blank">https:/
 /rfo.simpletix.com</a> for important information and to buy tickets. You MU
 ST have a ticket to attend this event\; tickets will not be sold at the doo
 r. Tickets are $50 per adult\, $45 for seniors (62+) and students\, and $40
  for members. Cost includes the Sugarloaf Ridge State Park parking fee. Ple
 ase note that tickets are non-refundable and cannot be used for future even
 ts.<br><br>RFO is operated by the Valley of the Moon Observatory Associatio
 n\, a 501(3)(c) nonprofit organization. All proceeds go toward maintaining 
 this beloved Sonoma County institution.
LAST-MODIFIED:20251114T163820Z
SEQUENCE:1
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Focus Night: Geminids Meteor Shower
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Robert Ferguson Observatory
